<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: BRADLEY PRAISES JANITORS AS 3-WEEK STRIKE 
ENDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Century City janitors ended a strike Tuesday by ratifying a labor contract with 
a large cleaning company and then held a rally where Los Angeles Mayor Tom 
Bradley and Councilman Zev Yaroslavsky praised them for their resoluteness 
during the three-week work stoppage. 
</P>
<P>
A tentative settlement negotiated Sunday means Service Employees International 
Union will represent approximately 500 janitors employed by International 
Service System Inc. in Los Angeles, including 180 janitors who work in 13 
office towers cleaned by ISS in Century City. 
</P>
<P>
Janitors will return to work Friday. The average janitor's pay will increase 
immediately from $4.50 an hour to $5.20, with health insurance and vacation 
benefits to start next spring, union officials said. "Fairness is all that has 
ever been requested . . . to bring about a living wage," Bradley told the 
rally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
