<HEADLINE>
<P>
USC LANDS CITY CO-MVP MCMACKIN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN LYNCH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reed McMackin, who helped lead Chatsworth High to a City Section baseball title 
this year, signed a national letter of intent Tuesday with USC. 
</P>
<P>
McMackin accepted a partial scholarship, choosing USC over UC Riverside and 
Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
The 6-foot-1, 190-pound right-hander also played first base at Chatsworth but 
will concentrate on pitching at USC. 
</P>
<P>
A visit to the USC campus this month pushed McMackin into the Trojan camp, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"I was in awe with all the tradition that goes with the school," he said. "It 
was like walking through history. They have a great baseball program and offer 
a great education. It seemed like the best opportunity for me." 
</P>
<P>
McMackin posted a 12-2 record with a 1.98 earned-run average this year and set 
school records for wins in a season and a career (22). He also batted .402 with 
28 runs batted in this year and shared the 4-A Division player of the year 
award with El Camino Real's Pat Treend. 
</P>
<P>
Chatsworth defeated El Camino Real, 3-2, for the 4-A title. JOHN LYNCH 
</P>
</TEXT>
