<P>
UNITED MAKES BID FOR NEW EUROPEAN ROUTES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ELK GROVE VILLAGE, Ill. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
United Airlines has asked the federal government for approval to serve Madrid 
and Manchester, England, from its hub at Washington Dulles International 
Airport. 
</P>
<P>
United said it would provide daily service on each route, using Boeing 
767-200ER aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
Chairman Stephen M. Wolf said the applications were part of a United strategy 
to become "a truly global airline in the 1990s." 
</P>
<P>
He said United's hub at Dulles, in the Virginia suburbs of Washington, would 
permit Madrid and Manchester passengers to connect with United flights to 55 
other cities in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
In Europe, he said, United's strategy is to concentrate service on primary 
transportation centers in France, Germany, Italy and the United Kingdom and to 
expand to other European cities as opportunities arise and new aircraft become 
available. 
</P>
<P>
Berlin, Warsaw, Moscow and Milan/Rome also are on United's list of cities to be 
served, Wolf said. 
</P>
<P>
United also has been expanding aggressively in the Pacific. 
</P>
</TEXT>
